    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Necessary Deceptions</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stanley D Friedman letter replies to June editorial criticizing police impersonation of a TV crew to win release of children being held hostage in Luxembourg</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I fully understand the concern about the dangers of impersonating journalists expressed in your June 6 editorial ''A Dangerous Masquerade.'' I agree that a government that has its undercover agents or troops wear press badges to gain advantage in conflicts with rebel armies threatens the free flow of information we have every right to expect.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I fully understand the concern about the dangers of impersonating journalists expressed in your June 6 editorial ''A Dangerous Masquerade.'' I agree that a government that has its undercover agents or troops wear press badges to gain advantage in conflicts with rebel armies threatens the free flow of information we have every right to expect.</p>
        <p>But in the Luxembourg hostage situation in which 37 children from a day care center and three teachers were held hostage by a gunman demanding a television interview, I feel that the action of the Luxembourg police to impersonate a television crew was justified, if it was the surest and safest way to rescue the hostages.</p>
        <p>Perhaps other parents and grandparents will agree that in this particular situation, saving the lives of the children and their teachers was paramount.</p>
        <p>STANLEY D. FRIEDMAN  Elmhurst, Queens, June 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
